  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "### Component\n\nFoundryup\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\n_No response_\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\nfoundryup\n\n### Operating System\n\nmacOS (Intel)\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nIt is custom that people use grep's `-n` option by default, usually set in their shell config.\r\n\r\nE.g.:\r\n```bash\r\n# .zshrc\r\nexport GREP_OPTIONS=\"-n --color\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis makes grep add the relative line number to the output, resulting in the following call messing up the `foundryup` script:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n$ curl -sSf \"https://api.github.com/repos/foundry-rs/foundry/git/refs/tags/nightly\" \\\r\n        | grep -Eo '\"sha\"[^,]*' \\\r\n        | grep -Eo '[^:]*$' \\\r\n        | tr -d '\"' \\\r\n        | tr -d ' '\r\n1:f5e5eb52f62928c5b4daeec0fe963ad7f88cb464\r\n```\r\n\r\nConsequently, `1:f5e5eb52f62928c5b4daeec0fe963ad7f88cb464` is not a valid SHA, so `foundryup` will fail to download the corresponding archive.\r\n\r\nThe solution would be to remove that unnecessary part, using `cut`. E.g.,:\r\n\r\n```diff\r\n$ curl -sSf \"https://api.github.com/repos/foundry-rs/foundry/git/refs/tags/nightly\" \\\r\n        | grep -Eo '\"sha\"[^,]*' \\\r\n        | grep -Eo '[^:]*$' \\\r\n        | tr -d '\"' \\\r\n-        | tr -d ' '\r\n+        | tr -d ' ' \\\r\n+        | cut -d ':' -f 2\r\nf5e5eb52f62928c5b4daeec0fe963ad7f88cb464\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis solution works for people who use the `-n` option and those who don't.",
